||title=[[List of Byzantine emperors|Emperor of the Romans]]}}
'''Symbatios''' ({{lang-el|Συμβάτιος}}, from the [[Armenian language|Armenian]] ''Smbat''), variously also '''Sabbatios''' (Σαββάτιος) or '''Sambates''' (Σαμβάτης) in some sources,<ref name="PmbZ"/> was the eldest son of the [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Leo V the Armenian]] ({{reign|813|820}}). Soon after the coronation of his father, he was crowned co-emperor and renamed '''Constantine''' (Κωνσταντῖνος). He reigned nominally along with his father until the latter's deposition in 820, after which he was [[exile]]d to [[Prote]], one of the [[Princes Islands]], as a [[monk]].

==Biography==
Symbatios was the eldest son of the emperor [[Leo V the Armenian]] ({{reign|813|820}}) and his wife, [[Theodosia, wife of Leo V|Theodosia]].<ref name="PmbZ"/> His father was an [[Armenians|Armenian]] commander in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] service, possibly descended from the [[Gnuni]] family. He had risen to high command as a protégé of [[Bardanes Tourkos]], but deserted him when the latter rebelled against [[Nikephoros I]] ({{reign|802|811}}).{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=196–197}}{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=[https://www.degruyter.com/view/PMBZ/PMBZ15402 Leon V. (#4244/corr.)]}} His mother was also of Armenian origin, the daughter of the ''[[patrikios]]'' [[Arsaber]] who attempted an unsuccessful usurpation against Nikephoros I in 808.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=[https://www.degruyter.com/view/PMBZ/PMBZ11686 Arsaber (#600)], [https://www.degruyter.com/view/PMBZ/PMBZ19038 Theodosia (#7790)]}} As he was a child at the time of his father's accession to the throne, Symbatios was born sometime between 800 and 810. [[Michael I Rhangabes]] ({{reign|811|813}}), the son-in-law and successor of Nikephoros I, was likely the boy's godfather.<ref name="PmbZ">{{harvnb|PmbZ|loc=[https://www.degruyter.com/view/PMBZ/PMBZ15078 Konstantinos (Symbatios) (#3925)]}}.</ref>{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|p=197}} 

At the head of a military revolt following the disastrous [[Battle of Versinikia]] against the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgars]], Leo deposed Michael I on 11 July 813 and was crowned emperor on the next day.{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=188–189}} Some time after{{efn|The sources do not provide an exact date on the coronation of Symbatios. The [[Scriptor Incertus]] simply mentions that "when the feast days arrived he crowned his son, still young, and named Symbates he lied calling him Constantine" ({{lang|grc|φθασάντων τῶν ἑορτῶν ἔστεψεν τὸν υἱὸν αὐτοῦ μικρὸν ὄντα, καὶ ἐπονομαζόμενον Συμβάτην ἐψεύσατο λέγων ὅτι Κωνσταντῖνος καλεῖται}}). This event is mentioned along with the Bulgar raids into Thrace during the winter of 813/814. As a result, scholars like [[J. B. Bury]],{{sfn|Bury|1912|pp=58–59}} [[Robert Browning (Byzantinist)|Robert Browning]],{{sfn|Browning|1965|p=401}} and [[Warren Treadgold]]{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=202–204}} placed the coronation during Christmas 813, but the ''[[Prosopography of the Byzantine Empire]]'' places it in April 814, during Easter.{{sfn|PBE|loc=[http://www.pbe.kcl.ac.uk/person/p4340 Konstantinos 29]}} }} he had Symbatios crowned co-emperor and renamed Constantine. The latter name was not chosen randomly: aside from it being a traditional Byzantine imperial name dating back to [[Constantine the Great]], the assembled troops now publicly acclaimed the emperors "Leo and Constantine", evoking openly the [[Byzantine Iconoclasm|iconoclast]] emperor [[Leo III the Isaurian]] ({{reign|717|741}}) and his son [[Constantine V]] ({{reign|741|775}}).<ref name="PmbZ"/>{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|p=203}} 

Although prior to his accession Leo had given written guarantees to the [[iconophile]] patriarch [[Nikephoros I of Constantinople|Nikephoros I]] that he would not attempt to overthrow iconophile church doctrine,{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|p=199}} the naming of the new co-emperor was a clear statement of intent to the contrary. Leo's motivations can only be guessed at, but at a time when the environs of [[Constantinople]] itself were being raided by the Bulgar ruler [[Krum]], the military successes achieved by the iconoclast emperors contrasted starkly with the defeats suffered by the recent iconophile regimes. Leo was also a military man, and the memory of the iconoclast emperors was particularly cherished by the army, where many still adhered to iconoclasm.{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=201–204}}{{sfn|Bury|1912|pp=57–59}}

On 14 March 814, Leo forced the resignation of Patriarch Nikephoros I, and appointed the pro-iconoclast [[Theodotos Melissenos]], the son of one of Constantine V's brother-in-law's, in his place.{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=212–213}} The new patriarch convened a [[Council of Constantinople (815)|Church council]] in Constantinople, which overturned the [[Second Council of Nicaea]] and reinstated the ban on the veneration of [[icon]]s. The council was presided over by Theodotos, while Constantine attended it as his father's representative.<ref name="PmbZ"/>{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|p=213}} In 819/820, he issued, jointly with his father, a [[novel (Roman law)|novel]] on [[marriage law]].<ref name="PmbZ"/>

Leo the Armenoian was assassinated on 25 December 820 by the supporters of [[Michael the Amorian]], who had been imprisoned for conspiring against Leo. Michael was released from prison and proclaimed emperor on the same night.{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|pp=224–225}}{{sfn|Bury|1912|pp=48–54}} The new emperor banished Constantine, along with his mother and three brothers, Basil, Gregory, and Theodosios, to the island of [[Prote]], one of the [[Princes Islands]] in the [[Sea of Marmara]]. There, the four brothers were [[political mutilation in Byzantine culture|castrated]] to make them incapable of claiming the throne in the future, and [[tonsure]]d. They spent the rest of their days there as monks, although Michael the Amorian allowed them to keep part of the proceeds from their confiscated estates for their and their servants' upkeep.<ref name="PmbZ"/>{{sfn|Treadgold|1988|p=224}} Basil and Gregory are still mentioned as iconophiles in 847,{{sfn|PBE|loc=[http://www.pbe.kcl.ac.uk/person/p1765 Basilios 54] & [http://www.pbe.kcl.ac.uk/person/p3163 Gregorios 70]}} but nothing further is known of Constantine.<ref name="PmbZ"/>{{sfn|PBE|loc=[http://www.pbe.kcl.ac.uk/person/p4340 Konstantinos 29]}}

