{{Chinese name|[[Fei (surname)|Fei]]}}
'''Fei Xin''' ({{zh|费信}}; ca. 1385 - after 1436) was a member of the military personnel of the fleet of the [[Ming dynasty]] admiral [[Zheng He]], known as the author of a book about the countries visited by Chinese ships.
==Biography== Little is known about Fei Xin's life.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=18}} His family originated from [[Kunshan]], in today's [[Jiangsu]] Province. Based on other dates mentioned by him, it is likely that he was born in the 17th year of the [[Hongwu Emperor|Hongwu era]] (1385), although some authors' calculation give 1388 as the date of his birth.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}} He taught himself the [[Arabic]] language.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} <!-- no mention of that anywhere in Ptak (1996) -->
According to what Fei Xin says in the preface to his book, his family was poor. His older brother was called up to serve at the nearby [[Taicang]] garrison, but soon died, and young Fei Xin took his place, in or after 1398.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}}{{sfn|Pelliot|1933|pp=264-268}} [[J.J.L. Duyvendak]] speculated that the Fei brothers had been conscripted as a punishment for some political or other offense of their father or grandfather; there is no actual proof of that, but Fei Xin's later biographer, [[Roderich Ptak]], thought that that wasn't impossible.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}}
While a soldier, he managed to find time for study.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}} [[Taicang]] being the lower-Yangtze base of the Zheng He fleet, Fei Xin ended up sailing with the fleet to the South-East Asia and the Indian Ocean four times.{{sfn|Pelliot|1933|pp=264-268}}
Fei Xin is primarily known as the author of the book ''[[Xingcha Shenglan]]'' (''Description of the Starry Raft''; preface dated 1436), in which he recorded what he had seen on his 4 voyages to the southern seas.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}}{{sfn|Pelliot|1933|pp=264-268}} There are no known mentions of his activities at later dates than 1436, and there is no information about the actual date of his death either.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=19}}
According to Ptak, there is no reliable information about Fei Xin's religion. Ptak believes that it is unlikely that Fei Xin was a [[Muslim]], like [[Ma Huan]] or Zheng He himself. Fei Xin did conclude his book with the description of [[Mecca]], but this may have been just an emulation of Ma Huan's book's layout.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=16-17}}
Fei Xin's book exists in a number of different Ming-era editions.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=9-11}} It has been studied by many Chinese and foreign historians. The first English translation of his book was made by [[William Woodville Rockhill]], and published in the ''[[T'oung Pao]]'' in 1914-1915.{{sfn|Fei|1996|pp=20}}<ref>Rockhill's work, covering also numerous other sources, appeared in several installments. One of them is this: W. W. Rockhill, ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/4526442 Notes on the Relations and Trade of China with the Eastern Archipelago and the Coast of the Indian Ocean during the Fourteenth Century. Part II]. ''T'oung Pao'', Second Series, Vol. 16, No. 1 (Mar., 1915), pp. 61-159</ref> The most recent translation, based on a draft by [[J.V.G. Mills]], was edited and annotated by Roderich Ptak (1996).<ref>{{harvnb|Fei|1996}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Ma Huan]], another participants of Zheng He's expeditions who wrote a book * [[Chen Cheng (Ming Dynasty)]], the Chinese diplomat who left an account of his travels to [[Samarqand]] and [[Herat]] in the same time period
