'''Kenneth Fetterman''' is a famous art [[scam artist]] who occasionally partnered with [[Kenneth Walton (writer)|Kenneth Walton]] to sell very expensive [[Art forgery|counterfeit art]] on rigged auctions on [[eBay]].<ref>Scheide, R.V., [http://www.newsreview.com/reno/Content?oid=oid%3A17922 "Prisoner of love"], ''[[Sacramento News and Review]]'', URL retrieved 2006-12-13.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Fake' puts the focus on Seattle art con man again|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/article/Fake-puts-the-focus-on-Seattle-art-con-man-again-1208710.php|publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=September 21, 2015|date=July 12, 2006}}</ref>
One of his partners in the [[shill]] bidding was Kenneth Walton, who had, in May 2000, sold a fake painting that was at the time the highest price ever paid for a painting in an [[Online auction business model|online auction]]. It was supposedly the undiscovered work of the late Northern California artist [[Richard Diebenkorn]]. However, the fraud was discovered, and after Walton was investigated, it was uncovered that Walton, Scott Beach, and Fetterman were involved in a shill bidding ring and that Fetterman had faked many paintings. After running from the authorities using various aliases and living off of his fake paintings he was selling on eBay, he was finally caught indicted by a [[Grand jury#Federal grand juries|federal grand jury]] for rigging art auctions on eBay. In May 2004, Fetterman was sentenced to nearly four years in federal prison.<ref>Melley, Brian, [https://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2004-05-27-ebay-art-fraud_x.htm "California eBay scam artist sent to federal prison"], ''[[USA Today]],'' 2004-05-27, URL retrieved 2006-12-13.</ref>
